Vinho Verde is by far my most favorite wine, especially white variety.

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests): 1 - fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3) 2 - volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3) 3 - citric acid (g / dm^3) 4 - residual sugar (g / dm^3) 5 - chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3 6 - free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3) 7 - total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3) 8 - density (g / cm^3) 9 - pH 10 - sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3) 11 - alcohol (% by volume) Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Column X is contains order numbers, can be removed.

verde <- subset(verde,select = -c(X))

Based on the initial data description, vatiable quality is a categorical parameter. In this dataset its represented as integer, so I am going to convert it to a factor.

verde$quality <- factor(verde$quality)

New columns

Apart from quality, the remaining categories have continuous values. Column X is a counter and will not be considered in the analysis. Citric.acid has minimum value of 0, which may be an error.

Also, since wines are usually classified based on their sweetnes. An excellent guide how to assess sweetness of wine, depending on pH, sugar and acid content. https://drinkriesling.com/tasteprofile/thescale

#  sugar/acid ratio
verde$sugar_acid.ratio <- verde$residual.sugar/(verde$fixed.acidity +
                                                  verde$volatile.acidity +
                                                  verde$citric.acid)
verde$sweetnes <- with (verde, ifelse(sugar_acid.ratio<1
                                      ,ifelse(pH<3.1,"Extra Dry"
                                             ,ifelse(pH<3.3,"Dry"
                                                    ,ifelse(pH<3.5,"Medium Dry","Medium Sweet")
                                                    )
                                             )
                                      ,ifelse(sugar_acid.ratio<=2
                                              ,ifelse(pH<=2.9,"Dry"
                                                     ,ifelse(pH<3.3,"Medium Dry","Medium Sweet")
                                                     )
                                              ,ifelse(sugar_acid.ratio<4.1
                                                      ,ifelse(pH<=2.8,"Dry"
                                                             ,ifelse(pH<=2.9,"Medium Dry"
                                                                    ,ifelse(pH<3.3,"Medium Sweet","Sweet")
                                                                    )
                                                             )
                                                      ,ifelse(pH<=2.8,"Medium Dry"
                                                              ,ifelse(pH<=2.9,"Medium Sweet","Sweet")
                                                              )
                                                      )
                                              )
                                      )
                        )

Initial plots

For a quick overview I am going to plot all columns using qplot in a loop. The advantage of using qplot is that it will decide by itself if to plot histogram or bar chart depenting on input data.

for (i in names(verde)){
  print(qplot(data = verde, verde[,i], xlab=i, bins=200))
}

qplot(data=verde, sugar_acid.ratio, bins=1000)
